The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Sports | Das capitalises as Kundu wilts
                                                                                                                       7                                        Das capitalises as Kundu wilts
            A CORRESPONDENT            The winners of The Telegraph Schools Chess Championship, presented by Himani Sona Chandi Chawayanprash, with chief guest Dav Whatmore at Gorky Sadan on Tuesday. A Telegraph picture                           
	Calcutta: Sayantan Das of Scottish Church Collegiate School pipped Satyajit Kundu to the post on Tuesday, in the final round of The Telegraph Schools Chess Championship, presented by Himani Sona Chandi Chawayanprash and organised by Alekhine Chess Club, at Gorky Sadan.         
	Satyajit, of Vivekananda Mission School, had played with elan till the penultimate round, and needed only a draw against Sayantan to win the title. But he crumbled under pressure, overlooking a knight sacrifice by his opponent, and was checkmated.         
	With the victory, Sayantan, a class VIII student, emerged champion with nine points, and was richer by Rs 20,000, besides a glittering trophy. Satyajit had to be content with the runner-up trophy and a cash prize of Rs 15,000.         
	Chandrasish Majumdar of St Xaviers Collegiate School tried hard for a win against Asian Under-12 champion Diptayan Ghosh of South Point, but could not succeed. Chandrasish had to settle for a draw and the third place.         
	Prince Bajaj of Delhi Public School, Ghaziabad, who had a cent percent score till the seventh round, outwitted Prakash Ved in the last round to finish fourth.         
	Abdullah Al-Saif of Bangladesh, who missed the first round, ended the championship on 8.5 points, and was placed fifth. Al-Saif, along with Diptayan Ghosh, who was placed sixth, were the only unbeaten participants .         
	Eight-year-old Mitrabha Guha, who finished 19th despite a loss in the last round, was the youngest player to finish in the main prize list.         
	South Point School won the best school trophy and Scottish Church Collegiate School won the second best school trophy.         
	Chandrasish won the Parimal Mukherjee trophy for the tournaments best game.         
	Among those present at the prize distribution were Aditya V. Agarwal, director, Emami group, Alekhine Chess Club president Kumar Shankar Bagchi, I.V. Korabayev, senior consul, Consulate General of Russian Federation in Calcutta, and Alexander V. Mazirka, director, Gorky Sadan.         
	TOP BOARD RESULTS         
	Satyajit Kundu (8.5) lost to Sayantan Das (9); Diptayan Ghosh (8) drew with Chandrasish Majumdar(8.5); Prakash Ved (7.5) lost to Prince Bajaj (8.5); Samrat Ghorai (7) lost to Abdullah Al-Saif (8.5); Saikat Dutta (7) lost to Aditya Chakraborty (8); Suvradeepta Das (7.5) drew with Vishal Iyer (7.5); Mitrbha Guha (7) lost to Debankan Dhara (8); Rishav Mitra (7) lost to Arpan Das (8); Aubhropratim Manna (7.5) beat Pavit Singh (7); Ikramul Haque Siam (7) drew with Krishna Teja N (7).                                                                                                                     
